# AWS Site-to-Site VPN Lab (Hybrid Connectivity)

## 1. AWS CONFIGURATION

### 1.1 Create VPC

* VPC Name: VPN Lab
* CIDR Block: 10.0.0.0/16
* Enable DNS Hostnames: Yes
* Enable DNS Resolution: Yes

---

### 1.2 Create Subnet(s)

* Subnet Name: Public Subnet
* CIDR Block: 10.0.1.0/24
* Availability Zone: us-east-1a

---

### 1.3 Route Table Configuration

* Route Table Name: Public Route Table
* Associate with Subnet: Public Subnet

Add route:

* Destination: 192.168.0.0/24
* Target: aws-vgw (name)

---

### 1.4 Launch EC2 Instance (Test Target)

* Instance Name: Test Instance
* Subnet: Public Subnet
* Private IP: 10.0.1.61

Security Group:
name: vpn-sg
* Allow ICMP (for ping testing) from 0.0.0.0/0
* Allow SSH (port 22) from 0.0.0.0/0 

---

### 1.5 Create Virtual Private Gateway (VGW)

* VGW Name: aws-vgw
* Attach VGW to: VPN Lab

---

### 1.6 Create Customer Gateway (CGW)

* CGW Name: home-cgw
* Routing: Static
* Public IP: 96.230.78.21
* ASN: 65000

---

### 1.7 Create Site-to-Site VPN Connection

* VPN Name: site-to-site-vpn
* Target Gateway: aws-vgw
* Customer Gateway: home-cgw
* Routing Options: Static

Static Route:

* 192.168.0.0/24

---

### 1.8 Download VPN Configuration

* Vendor: Cisco ISR
* Save configuration file for reference
vpn-01f8cd298e81015d2.txt

---



---

### 1.10 Verify AWS VPN Status

* Navigate to VPN Connections
* Confirm both tunnels eventually show: UP

---

## 2. VERIZON ROUTER CONFIGURATION

### 2.1 Identify Network Details

* Router Gateway IP: 192.168.1.1 private, public 96.230.78.21

---


---

)

---

## 3. GNS3 / VMWARE CONFIGURATION

### 3.1 Topology

[LAN DEVICE] — [IOSv ROUTER] — [BRIDGED ADAPTER] — [VERIZON ROUTER] — INTERNET — AWS

---

### 3.2 Networking Mode

* Adapter Mode: Bridged
* IOSv WAN Interface

---

### 3.3 IOSv Interface Roles

* WAN Interface (G0/0): 192.168.1.100 (192.168.1.0/24 network)
* LAN Interface (G0/1): 192.168.0.1 (default gateway of 192.168.0.0/24 LAN network)
-

### 3.4 LAN Configuration

* LAN Network: 192.168.0.0/24
* Test Device IP: 192.168.0.10 (static)

---

### 3.5 NAT Design

* Enable NAT overload for internet access
* Configure NAT exemption for:

  * 192.168.0.0/24 ↔ 10.0.0.0/16 deny NAT for this
  but allow NAT for 192.168.0.0/24 to anywhere else

---

### 3.6 VPN Tunnel Setup

Using AWS configuration file:

Configure:

* Tunnel 1 (Primary)
* Tunnel 2 (Secondary)

Each includes:

* Peer IP
* Pre-shared key
* Inside tunnel IPs (169.254.x.x)
Tunnel 1
outside 34.193.85.87
inside 169.254.222.168/30
Tunnel 2
inside 100.50.211.87
outside 169.254.81.232/30
* Transform set
* IPsec profile
* Tunnel interface

---

### 3.7 Routing Configuration

* Add static routes to:

  * 10.0.0.0/16 via Tunnel1
  * 10.0.0.0/16 via Tunnel2

---

### 3.8 High Availability (Failover)

Configure:

* IP SLA probes to AWS tunnel endpoints
* Track objects linked to SLA
* Static routes tied to track state

Result:

* Automatic failover between tunnels

---

### 3.9 Validation

From LAN device labeled (On-Prem PC):

* Ping and SSH to Test Instance 10.0.1.61 using private IP


Reverse the process
Ping and ssh into On-Prem PC from Test Instance using private IP
Ping and ssh into router's int g0/1 int of 192.168.0.1 from Test Instance as well

Verify:

* Tunnel 1 packet counters increase
* Tunnel 2 establishes and passes traffic
* Both IPsec tunnels show ACTIVE

---

## 4. FINAL ARCHITECTURE

192.168.0.0/24
↓
IOSv Router (Routing + NAT + IPsec)
↓
Home Router (NAT + Port Forwarding)
↓
Internet
↓
AWS VGW
↓
10.0.0.0/16

---

## 5. PROJECT OUTCOME

* Implemented Site-to-Site VPN between on-prem and AWS
* Configured dual IPsec tunnels for redundancy
* Enabled NAT traversal (UDP 4500)
* Implemented SLA-based failover
* Validated bidirectional connectivity

---

## 6. NOTES (OPTIONAL)

* Tunnel 1 acts as primary path
* Tunnel 2 acts as backup or secondary path
* AWS VPN charges apply while connection exists
* VGW itself does not incur cost

